author: @LabGecko
text: Great video series! I think this could help get a more intuitive feel for how machine learning works. The only problem I'm having is that you seem to tell us what you're going to do a lot. Brief overviews are fine now and then, but I'd rather just see you do it, and explain it as you do it. Also, I'm taking back my previous vote on a different video when you asked if we'd like copy-paste + explain, or to see you debug. If it's basic syntax, then of course I'd rather copy+paste, but if it's an error that is logic or missing a header, etc., I think it's helpful to see you go through the process of fixing that. I watch videos to learn from other people's mistakes too. Thanks again for doing all these series! You got me going on Python in 2 days. That's impressive!

author: @sibyjoseplathottam4828
text: Glad to know that the model works. I finally managed to read (which you provided) and feed the data  into the Keras model using the tf dataset API and started training on my laptop. I will share my code if anybody is interested. Also another thing I noticed was that you don't seem to normalizing the xdata (image) by dividing it by 255 before feeding it to the CNN (unless I missed this part). Wouldn't this negatively affect the training?  A few things which I noticed could be improved: 1) The x data (image) is being stored as an uint8 datatype. But the y data  (one hot array) is being stored as float64 datatype. I think changing it to Bool datatype could reduce size of the .npy files. 2) The logic for issuing order to create buildings and units could me made into a general method. It could take as argument the type of building/unit to be created and it's per-requisites.

author: @parseeval
text: I wonder two things: first thing is this ai is unable to see "stacked" units clearly. It is unable to determine if there is a worker close to a military unit for example. Would it be useful to draw the units with a certain alpha so there is a learnable color for that and many other cases by simply mixing the original colors? And the seccond thing is if it would be useful to have a generic color code instead of hardcoding the color for every type of unit. I guess there is some enum value for each type of entity and if one calculates a kind of "color hash" on two channels and add the team on the third, this would be a neat, non-spaghetti code to have a unique, learnable color for every type of unit and every mutation of a unit (like the three different kinds terran of command centers I read about in another comment). What do you think?

text: So watching through, the code on this run through was set to Difficulty.Easy. So i'm following along, and doing my version a bit different. Inputs are (Economy, Military Strength, Research).
